{{orphan|date=July 2013}}
In [[software engineering]] a '''binade''' is a term used<ref>Number of solutions to A<sup>2</sup>+B<sup>2</sup>=C<sup>2</sup>+C in a binade, [http://hal.inria.fr/inria-00071634/en/ HAL]</ref><ref>Idempotent Binary–>Decimal–>Binary Conversion, Prof. W. Kahan, [http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~wkahan/Math128/BinDecBin.pdf]</ref> to describe the set of numbers in a binary [[IEEE 754]] floating-point format that all have the same exponent, i.e., a binade is the interval [2<sup>n</sup>, 2<sup>n+1</sup>) for some value of n.

